The sample mean \(\bar{X}\) for a random sample of size \(n = 12\) from a uniform distribution on \((0,1)\) has a mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma^2 / n\), where \(\sigma^2 = 1/12\) is the variance of the uniform distribution. Thus, the variance of \(\bar{X}\) is \((1/12)/12 = 1/144\), and the standard deviation is \(\sqrt{1/144} = 1/12\).

By the Central Limit Theorem, \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed. The probability \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)\) is approximated by standardizing to a standard normal variable. The standardized bounds are:
- Lower bound: \((0.5 - 0.5) / (1/12) = 0\)
- Upper bound: \((2/3 - 0.5) / (1/12) = (1/6) / (1/12) = 2\)

Thus, \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3) = P(0 \leq Z \leq 2)\), where \(Z\) is a standard normal variable. Using the standard normal distribution, \(P(0 \leq Z \leq 2) = \Phi(2) - \Phi(0) \approx 0.9772 - 0.5 = 0.4772\).

The result is rounded to four decimal places as a reasonable approximation.

