Solution: The problem requires a lower bound for \(P(|Y / n - 0.25| < 0.05)\) when \(Y \sim b(n, 0.25)\) and \(n = 500\).

Using Chebyshev's inequality, a lower bound is derived. For the sample proportion \(Y/n\), the mean is \(\mu = p = 0.25\) and the variance is \(\sigma^2 = p(1-p)/n = (0.25)(0.75)/500 = 0.1875/500 = 0.000375\).

Chebyshev's inequality states that \(P(|X - \mu| \geq \epsilon) \leq \sigma^2 / \epsilon^2\), so \(P(|X - \mu| < \epsilon) \geq 1 - \sigma^2 / \epsilon^2\).

Here, \(\epsilon = 0.05\), so \(\epsilon^2 = 0.0025\). Then, \(\sigma^2 / \epsilon^2 = 0.000375 / 0.0025 = 0.15\).

Thus, \(P(|Y/n - 0.25| < 0.05) \geq 1 - 0.15 = 0.85\).

This gives a lower bound of 0.85.

